-- AU Optronics, Formosa, Genting, HSBC, Posco: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview
-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 2010-12-21T20:46:11Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-21/formosa-genting-hsbc-posco-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in  Asian trading , excluding Japan.
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  AU Optronics Corp.  (2409 TT): The company’s unit, Toppan
CFI (Taiwan) Co., plans to invest $167 million in a color-filter
plant in Kunshan, China, the Hsinchu, Taiwan-based AU Optronics
said in a statement to the Taiwan stock exchange. The stock
climbed 0.3 percent to NT$30.65.  Far Eastern New Century Corp.  (1402 TT): The company’s unit,
Far Eastern Resources Development Ltd., sold six plots of land
of 3,003 square meters in Banchiao city in Taipei County to
affiliate Far Eastern Medical Foundation for NT$433 million ($14
million), the parent company said in a statement to the local
exchange. Far Eastern, a textile producer, rose 3.3 percent to
NT$49.15.  Formosa Chemicals & Fibre Corp.  (1326 TT): The producer of
petrochemical products plans to invest a total of $241 million
in two wholly-owned Chinese subsidiaries in Ningbo city through
an investment arm, according to a statement to the Taiwan Stock
Exchange. Formosa Chemicals fell 0.4 percent to NT$95.60.  Genting Malaysia Bhd.  (GENM MK): The casino and hotel group
said it has been collaborating with a partner to explore
opportunities in Vietnam, according to a company statement. The
company was responding to media reports that the Genting group
and Vina Capital has received government approval for a casino
resort project in Hoi An city. Genting advanced 0.3 percent to
3.29 ringgit.  HSBC Holdings Plc  (5 HK): Europe’s biggest bank agreed to
sell 80.1 percent of its U.K.-based global real estate and
infrastructure private equity fund management business to the
unit’s senior management team. The business had gross assets of
about 35.1 million pounds ($54.4 million) as of June 30, HSBC
said. The stock gained 1.1 percent to HK$80.15.  KNM Group Bhd.  (KNMG MK): The Malaysian oil and gas
services provider said it secured a 2.19 billion ringgit ($699.7
million) contract to build a biomass energy and waste recycling
center in Peterborough, United Kingdom, according to a company
statement. This contract with Peterborough Renewable Energy Ltd.
is for four years, KNM said. KNM slid 1.8 percent to 2.69
ringgit.  Posco  (005490 KS): South Korea’s biggest steelmaker hasn’t
decided whether to bid for a stake in  Korea Express Co.  (000120
KS), it said in a regulatory filing. MoneyToday earlier reported
Posco is considering buying a stake in the logistics company
after Asiana Airlines Inc. and Daewoo Engineering & Construction
Co. said last week they may sell their respective 24 percent
holdings. Posco jumped 5.1 percent to 493,000 won and Korea
Express rose 3.6 percent to 95,400 won.  Wilmar International Ltd.  (WIL SP): The world’s largest
palm-oil trader said a unit signed an agreement with  Kerry
Properties (China) Ltd.  (683 HK) and  Shangri-La China Ltd.  (69
HK) to set up joint ventures to develop properties in China’s
Liaoning province. Wilmar fell 0.5 percent to S$5.92. Kerry
Properties gained 0.6 percent to HK$40.80 and Shangri-La
advanced 0.5 percent to HK$20.95.  To contact the reporter on this story:
